WEBVTT

00:02.000 --> 00:04.580
Meredith: Unless you're paid
to be there,

00:04.580 --> 00:06.790
no one ever wants
to go into an O.R.

00:06.790 --> 00:08.500
It's freezing, you're naked,

00:08.500 --> 00:10.170
and a stranger
will be cutting into your body

00:10.170 --> 00:11.170
with knives.

00:11.170 --> 00:12.830
♪ I wanna go up, up, and away ♪

00:12.830 --> 00:14.790
This is not it.
It's not on here, okay?

00:14.790 --> 00:16.830
But what patients don't know

00:16.830 --> 00:19.620
and what we try to keep them
from knowing is...

00:19.620 --> 00:21.080
Why shouldn't that
be on there?

00:21.080 --> 00:23.250
...sometimes it's just
as terrifying for us.

00:23.250 --> 00:26.420
♪ I just wanna show them
I can make it on my own ♪

00:26.420 --> 00:27.580
[ Gasps ]

00:27.580 --> 00:28.620
♪ I wanna go up, up, and away ♪

00:28.620 --> 00:30.000
What?

00:30.000 --> 00:32.330
Traumas, heart surgery,

00:32.330 --> 00:34.000
anything to do
with the pancreas.

00:34.000 --> 00:36.460
♪♪

00:36.460 --> 00:38.170
♪ A-dah-dah-dah... ♪

00:38.170 --> 00:41.210
Any surgeon who says they're
not afraid of those is lying.

00:41.210 --> 00:43.580
♪♪

00:43.580 --> 00:46.620
♪ 97 more days ♪

00:46.620 --> 00:48.750
♪ Until I'm living out
in the world ♪

00:48.750 --> 00:50.210
You just wrote that.

00:50.210 --> 00:51.830
But no matter how risky
the surgery...

00:51.830 --> 00:54.210
♪ I'll turn my problems
into pearls ♪

00:54.210 --> 00:56.670
[ Sighs ]
...no matter how scared
you might be...

00:56.670 --> 01:00.380
♪ ...the stories
how people run back home ♪

01:00.380 --> 01:03.920
...your job is to reassure
your patient...

01:03.920 --> 01:06.580
♪ Up, up, and away ♪

01:06.580 --> 01:09.750
♪♪

01:09.750 --> 01:12.710
♪ And dah-dah-dah-dah,
dah-dah-dah-dah ♪

01:14.380 --> 01:17.120
...and tell them, "Everything
is going to be okay."

01:17.120 --> 01:20.880
♪♪

01:20.880 --> 01:24.080
♪ Dah-dah-dah-dah,
dah-dah-dah-dah ♪

01:24.080 --> 01:25.670
Whether you believe it or not.

01:25.670 --> 01:28.250
♪♪

01:28.250 --> 01:33.790
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪

01:33.790 --> 01:39.120
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪

01:39.120 --> 01:44.670
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪

01:44.670 --> 01:48.460
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪

01:48.460 --> 01:50.710
[ Sighs ]

01:50.710 --> 01:53.710
Uh, hey. Has -- Has Richard been
getting the hiccups lately?

01:55.210 --> 01:56.710
I don't know.
Why?

01:56.710 --> 01:59.330
[ Sighs ] Could be a symptom
of Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease.

01:59.330 --> 02:01.170
Less than 350 Americans
get it each year.

02:01.170 --> 02:03.330
There's no 1-hertz spikes
on the EEG.

02:03.330 --> 02:04.880
The RT Quick Panel
come back yet?

02:04.880 --> 02:06.500
Um...ugh.

02:06.500 --> 02:08.830
Not sure.
My tablet just died.

02:08.830 --> 02:09.920
Okay.
I'm gonna get another one.

02:09.920 --> 02:11.000
I'll be right back.

02:15.210 --> 02:16.500
Permission slip.

02:16.500 --> 02:18.080
Zola's field trip
to the zoo.

02:18.080 --> 02:20.040
Oh.
Well, that's next week, but...

02:20.040 --> 02:21.420
This is next week.

02:21.420 --> 02:23.750
Oh.

02:23.750 --> 02:25.540
Has DeLuca been sleeping?

02:25.540 --> 02:27.620
I don't know.

02:27.620 --> 02:29.500
You're okay with that?

02:29.500 --> 02:30.500
Are you here to help?

02:31.920 --> 02:34.330
When my mom was sick,

02:34.330 --> 02:36.500
I was so blinded
by my need to cure her

02:36.500 --> 02:39.120
that I couldn't accept the fact
that she was dying.

02:39.120 --> 02:40.380
And instead
of caring for her,

02:40.380 --> 02:43.670
I put her through
all this unnecessary testing,

02:43.670 --> 02:45.210
and I hurt her.

02:45.210 --> 02:46.790
That's what you told me.

02:46.790 --> 02:48.880
Right, but she had
an actual diagnosis.

02:50.830 --> 02:52.170
It's Alzheimer's,
Meredith.

02:52.170 --> 02:53.830
I do not believe
that it is.

02:53.830 --> 02:56.420
Well,
Amelia and Koracick do.

02:56.420 --> 02:58.460
So Catherine's
taking Richard home today.

02:58.460 --> 03:00.750
♪♪

03:00.750 --> 03:01.960
[ Sighs ]

03:01.960 --> 03:07.290
♪♪

03:14.210 --> 03:16.880
[ Amelia sighs ]

03:16.880 --> 03:19.290
Oh, hey, Mommy.

03:19.290 --> 03:21.250
Nope. Unh-unh.

03:21.250 --> 03:23.580
You call me Baby Daddy.

03:23.580 --> 03:26.500
And now I will never
do that again.

03:26.500 --> 03:28.750
Did you already finish up
your arthroscopy?

03:28.750 --> 03:30.040
Yeah.
Cruised through it.

03:30.040 --> 03:32.920
Still have clinic
and some post-ops, but...

03:32.920 --> 03:34.960
how 'bout
an early movie?

03:34.960 --> 03:36.500
Then Angelini's.

03:36.500 --> 03:38.290
Take advantage of still being
a party of two.

03:38.290 --> 03:41.040
I have a DBS, and I'm hoping
to fit in a corpectomy.

03:41.040 --> 03:43.790
You had contractions last week
over an open brain.

03:43.790 --> 03:45.330
So?

03:45.330 --> 03:47.620
So, don't you think it's time
to lighten the load?

03:47.620 --> 03:48.880
I am.

03:48.880 --> 03:50.580
Well, you can return
to surgery

03:50.580 --> 03:52.120
whenever you want
after this baby is born.

03:52.120 --> 03:54.120
My body won't
come back so fast,

03:54.120 --> 03:56.330
so I gotta squeeze in
as much as I can.

03:56.330 --> 03:58.540
Dr. Shepherd,
O.R. 3 is ready.

03:58.540 --> 04:01.380
Alright.
I will be there in a minute.

04:01.380 --> 04:03.120
[ Exhales deeply ]

04:03.120 --> 04:05.080
Might be more like ten.

04:05.080 --> 04:06.920
Shut up!

04:06.920 --> 04:09.460
[ Chuckles ]

04:09.460 --> 04:10.960
And let me know
if there's any increase

04:10.960 --> 04:12.920
in Mr. Rojas'
chest tube output.

04:12.920 --> 04:14.670
You got it, Dr. Altman.

04:14.670 --> 04:17.380
And, um, congratulations,
about tonight.

04:17.380 --> 04:19.120
Even though marriage
is an outdated concept,

04:19.120 --> 04:20.540
I still think it's neat.

04:20.540 --> 04:21.620
Koracick: I've been busy.
Thanks.

04:21.620 --> 04:22.670
Owen: But it's
a simple request, Tom.

04:22.670 --> 04:24.080
Y-You need to calm down.
Calm down?

04:24.080 --> 04:25.210
What the hell is wrong with you?
I should've known.

04:25.210 --> 04:26.460
[ Scoffs ]
Known? Known what?

04:26.460 --> 04:27.710
What's -- What's wrong?

04:27.710 --> 04:29.880
He said he didn't see the e-mail
requesting time off.

04:29.880 --> 04:31.460
I saw the subject line.
It didn't seem urgent.

04:31.460 --> 04:33.710
Y-You're getting married,
what, in a few months?

04:33.710 --> 04:36.330
It's tonight, Tom.

04:36.330 --> 04:38.420
It's just a -- It's a
last-minute thing, you know?

04:38.420 --> 04:40.750
Some family members
for a backyard party.

04:40.750 --> 04:43.250
"Last-minute thing."
Well, that sounds elegant, Hunt.

04:43.250 --> 04:45.460
Well, it's exactly
what Teddy wanted.

04:45.460 --> 04:47.580
[ Sighs ]

04:47.580 --> 04:49.790
So, the time off, please?

04:49.790 --> 04:50.670
Sure.
Whatever you need.

04:50.670 --> 04:52.080
Owen: Thank you.

04:52.080 --> 04:53.710
I'll see you.
Yeah, okay.

04:56.540 --> 04:57.500
Thanks for the heads-up.

04:57.500 --> 04:58.500
Tom, I --
No, no, no.

04:58.500 --> 05:00.460
I'm -- I couldn't be happier
for you.

05:00.460 --> 05:03.580
♪♪

05:03.580 --> 05:05.620
Morning, Daya.

05:05.620 --> 05:06.580
How you doing today?

05:06.580 --> 05:07.920
I'd be better

05:07.920 --> 05:10.290
if I had a smiling photo
for this dating app.

05:10.290 --> 05:11.460
His, not mine.

05:11.460 --> 05:13.380
She signed me up
against my will.

05:13.380 --> 05:15.170
And you can see
how happy it makes me.

05:15.170 --> 05:16.880
Oh, right. You can't.
Fun!

05:16.880 --> 05:19.670
[ Chuckles ]
Daya Burman, 13,

05:19.670 --> 05:22.000
presents
with Moebius syndrome,

05:22.000 --> 05:23.540
a rare neurological condition

05:23.540 --> 05:26.000
that inhibits
facial expression and --

05:26.000 --> 05:28.500
And leaves me with
resting bitch face 24-7.

05:28.500 --> 05:30.380
Not true.
And language.

05:30.380 --> 05:31.790
You'd swear, too, if you could
only express your emotions

05:31.790 --> 05:33.580
through Bitmojis.

05:33.580 --> 05:35.080
Well, fortunately, we're gonna
change all that. Dr. Avery?

05:35.080 --> 05:37.330
Yes, we are,
because today,

05:37.330 --> 05:39.500
we are doing a bilateral
gracilis transfer,

05:39.500 --> 05:41.000
which means we're taking
the muscles and nerves

05:41.000 --> 05:42.540
from your legs...

05:42.540 --> 05:44.000
[ Keyboard clacks ]
Mm-hmm.

05:44.000 --> 05:45.080
...implanting them
onto your face.

05:45.080 --> 05:46.330
Sorry to interrupt...
Mm-hmm.

05:46.330 --> 05:47.750
...but we know the surgery.

05:47.750 --> 05:50.210
We've bailed on it four times
in the last year.

05:50.210 --> 05:51.960
And by "we," I mean --
[ Clears throat ]

05:53.670 --> 05:55.540
But I think
he's finally ready,

05:55.540 --> 05:57.580
and I want to get going
before he chickens out again.

05:57.580 --> 06:00.250
Last time, I barely got into
a gown when he changed his mind.

06:00.250 --> 06:02.620
Because you don't need
this surgery.

06:02.620 --> 06:04.250
You're beautiful
just the way you are.

06:04.250 --> 06:06.330
You've been scared of hospitals
since Mom died.

06:06.330 --> 06:08.210
But I start high school
next year,

06:08.210 --> 06:09.960
and I want to have friends.

06:09.960 --> 06:12.960
Friends I can laugh and cry with
and who understand me.

06:12.960 --> 06:14.540
Because right now,
no one understands me.

06:14.540 --> 06:15.830
I do,

06:15.830 --> 06:17.920
and I think
you're perfect.

06:17.920 --> 06:19.040
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

06:19.040 --> 06:20.710
Now we're talking.

06:20.710 --> 06:22.040
Look out, single ladies.

06:22.040 --> 06:24.420
Hey, just --
Promise not to
chicken out again

06:24.420 --> 06:26.250
and I won't post it.

06:26.250 --> 06:29.500
♪♪

06:29.500 --> 06:33.580
[ Siren wails ]

06:33.580 --> 06:35.040
[ Brakes screech ]

06:37.460 --> 06:39.750
21-year-old male. Took a
baseball bat to the chest.

06:39.750 --> 06:41.330
Blunt trauma?
Not exactly.

06:41.330 --> 06:42.750
[ Man groans ]

06:42.750 --> 06:44.170
[ Inhales sharply ]

06:44.170 --> 06:45.250
Oh, my God.
[ Gurney clatters ]

06:45.250 --> 06:46.830
[ Exhales sharply ]

06:46.830 --> 06:48.710
You should see
the other guy.

06:48.710 --> 06:50.460
He's totally fine.

06:52.170 --> 06:53.540
Okay, you --
Look, you don't understand.

06:53.540 --> 06:54.960
Alright? You're making
a huge mistake.

06:54.960 --> 06:56.620
DeLuca, this doesn't
concern you.

06:56.620 --> 06:59.000
Yes, it does concern me, okay?
R-Richard's my friend.

06:59.000 --> 07:01.250
You've had weeks
and have found nothing.

07:01.250 --> 07:02.290
I'm taking
my husband home.

07:02.290 --> 07:03.670
Even if it means
you're gonna kill him?

07:03.670 --> 07:04.830
'Cause that's what you're doing.
You know that, right?

07:04.830 --> 07:05.830
You --
Andrew!

07:05.830 --> 07:08.080
Take a walk.

07:08.080 --> 07:10.830
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

07:10.830 --> 07:13.210
I'm sorry, Catherine.
He's exhausted.

07:13.210 --> 07:15.120
We're all exhausted.

07:16.380 --> 07:17.710
This is hard enough
without the accusations.

07:17.710 --> 07:19.380
But -- But I told him
not to come up here.

07:19.380 --> 07:21.540
Yeah, 'cause he's so great
at following the rules.

07:22.750 --> 07:24.250
Okay, I-I'm not a child!

07:24.250 --> 07:27.040
I-It won't take long.
Just to the exit.

07:27.040 --> 07:28.790
Catherine: I'm taking you home,
sweetheart, remember?

07:28.790 --> 07:29.830
Look, I want to walk.

07:29.830 --> 07:31.500
Okay. Okay.

07:35.330 --> 07:36.620
Ooh! Man.
Ooh.

07:36.620 --> 07:38.710
Richard: Damn it!
Alright,
you just slipped.

07:38.710 --> 07:41.540
My leg fell asleep because
you people keep me in this bed.

07:41.540 --> 07:42.580
Are you okay?

07:42.580 --> 07:44.830
I just need a minute, okay...
Okay.

07:44.830 --> 07:46.670
'til I can get the feeling
back in my toes.

07:48.540 --> 07:50.920
What do you mean you have
no feeling in your toes?

07:50.920 --> 07:52.710
Your feet have never
fallen asleep?

07:52.710 --> 07:54.000
Humor me.

07:55.250 --> 07:58.540
They're -- They're numb
and tingly.

07:58.540 --> 08:00.380
Meredith, he just slipped.

08:00.380 --> 08:02.330
Well, what about your fingers?
Are your fingers numb?

08:04.420 --> 08:05.880
Mm.

08:05.880 --> 08:08.080
I'm gonna check your calf,
okay?

08:08.080 --> 08:10.330
♪♪

08:10.330 --> 08:12.120
Mm!

08:12.120 --> 08:14.960
Ohh!
Okay.

08:14.960 --> 08:17.790
Tingling in the extremities
and sensitivity to touch

08:17.790 --> 08:20.250
are not signs
of Alzheimer's.

08:20.250 --> 08:22.420
Definitely should do an EMG
to test his nerves.

08:22.420 --> 08:23.920
You really think
that's warranted, Grey?

08:23.920 --> 08:26.420
I do, because if I'm right,
then it gives us some hope.

08:26.420 --> 08:28.080
And if you're wrong,
then it's torture.

08:28.080 --> 08:30.960
I don't need
any more tests!

08:30.960 --> 08:32.790
[ Sighs ]

08:32.790 --> 08:35.420
♪♪

08:35.420 --> 08:37.120
Catherine...

08:37.120 --> 08:40.080
I know you don't want to
see him in pain.

08:40.080 --> 08:42.330
I don't want to
see him in pain.

08:42.330 --> 08:44.500
But are we really
willing to ignore this?

08:44.500 --> 08:50.330
♪♪

08:50.330 --> 08:51.120
Do it.

08:52.670 --> 08:55.290
Richard: [ Sighs ] Ugh.

08:55.290 --> 08:59.000
Baby, we have to.
We have to.

09:04.420 --> 09:06.460
Let's type and screen him.

09:06.460 --> 09:07.380
Let's get a chest X-ray
and a CT trauma series.

09:07.380 --> 09:08.580
Schmitt,
let's get the ultrasound

09:08.580 --> 09:09.580
so we can assess
the extent of this damage.

09:09.580 --> 09:11.170
[ Sighs ]
Catcher called for heat.

09:11.170 --> 09:12.420
Next thing I know -- Boom.

09:12.420 --> 09:13.670
Shards came at me
like a boomerang.

09:13.670 --> 09:15.040
Let's page cardio.

09:15.040 --> 09:16.960
It's in my heart?
We don't know.

09:16.960 --> 09:18.120
That's why
we paged cardio, alright?

09:18.120 --> 09:19.710
I-I can take that
for you.
Yeah.

09:19.710 --> 09:21.670
[ Bag rustles ]

09:21.670 --> 09:22.580
Cascades, huh?

09:22.580 --> 09:24.080
Yeah.

09:24.080 --> 09:25.750
My dream's to go
to the Mariners.

09:25.750 --> 09:27.000
Seems to be everybody's
dream these days.

09:28.380 --> 09:30.380
Okay,
ultrasound's unclear.

09:30.380 --> 09:32.330
We're gonna get you up to CT,
and let's book an O.R.

09:32.330 --> 09:33.920
An O.R.?
Trust me --

09:33.920 --> 09:35.290
you do not
want to be awake

09:35.290 --> 09:37.460
when I pull this thing
out of you, okay?

09:37.460 --> 09:38.880
You're gonna be fine.
Okay, let's move.

09:38.880 --> 09:39.920
Let's go.

09:41.120 --> 09:42.880
[ Monitor beeps, Richard sighs ]

09:42.880 --> 09:43.960
[ Device whirs, crackles ]

09:43.960 --> 09:46.380
So, you noticed
sensory deficit

09:46.380 --> 09:50.000
and an increased sensitivity
to pain, which means...

09:50.000 --> 09:52.380
The nervous system
is like an electrical grid.

09:52.380 --> 09:55.040
By sending a small charge
to certain areas,

09:55.040 --> 09:57.080
we can see if all those lines
are connected.

09:57.080 --> 09:59.080
Or if a power line is down.

09:59.080 --> 10:00.580
The shock of this
should send

10:00.580 --> 10:02.330
all ten of his little piggies
squealing.

10:02.330 --> 10:06.000
From one chief to another,
sorry.

10:06.000 --> 10:08.170
Oh! Ohh.

10:08.170 --> 10:09.500
Ohh.

10:09.500 --> 10:10.540
Adding more juice.

10:10.540 --> 10:12.620
[ Breathes sharply ]

10:12.620 --> 10:13.880
Aah!
Yeah.

10:13.880 --> 10:14.790
[ Device whirs, crackles ]

10:14.790 --> 10:16.380
Ohh!

10:16.380 --> 10:18.290
No motor output
going to the legs.

10:18.290 --> 10:19.540
[ Exhales sharply ]

10:19.540 --> 10:21.880
The test confirmed
what we saw with the fall,

10:21.880 --> 10:24.040
which is he has
severe acute onset

10:24.040 --> 10:26.210
motor and sensory
nerve degeneration,

10:26.210 --> 10:28.420
which is inconsistent
with an Alzheimer's diagnosis.

10:28.420 --> 10:30.210
I'd like to hear
from my neurosurgeons.

10:30.210 --> 10:32.210
Grey's right.
It's a fantastic catch.

10:32.210 --> 10:33.880
I'm also withdrawing
my Alzheimer's vote.

10:33.880 --> 10:35.080
I --
[ Inhales deeply ]

10:35.080 --> 10:36.080
It's not just his mind
that's failing him.

10:36.080 --> 10:37.080
It's his body.

10:37.080 --> 10:39.120
Not Alzheimer's?

10:39.120 --> 10:40.790
Oh, my God.
That-- That's fantastic.

10:40.790 --> 10:42.670
Well, what is it?
Where does that leave us?

10:42.670 --> 10:45.170
In neuroscience,
the official term is square one.

10:45.170 --> 10:46.620
We keep hunting.

10:46.620 --> 10:49.500
Right. Then we should start with
a sural nerve biopsy

10:49.500 --> 10:51.380
and re-check his pan-scan

10:51.380 --> 10:53.670
to rule out a --
an occult tumor

10:53.670 --> 10:56.000
and just try to determine

10:56.000 --> 10:58.380
what exactly
is destroying his nerves.

10:58.380 --> 11:00.380
Agreed.
[ Cellphone chimes ]

11:00.380 --> 11:03.420
Aw, damn it.
Trauma consult.

11:03.420 --> 11:05.750
Please keep me posted.
And thank you, Meredith.

11:05.750 --> 11:07.290
Thank you all.

11:07.290 --> 11:09.620
Okay, I am, uh, clearing
the rest of my schedule today.

11:09.620 --> 11:11.330
I'll meet you
in the O.R., Grey.

11:11.330 --> 11:13.290
Uh, let Koracick
know what you find.

11:13.290 --> 11:14.880
I'm gonna let him
take over.

11:14.880 --> 11:16.120
Oh, you don't have to tell me
I'm better than you, Shepherd.

11:16.120 --> 11:17.750
I know I am.
You're not.

11:17.750 --> 11:19.080
But my water just broke.

11:20.880 --> 11:23.170
Oh.
Oh.
Oh.

11:23.170 --> 11:25.710
Uh...you want a wheelchair?
You're gonna walk?

11:25.710 --> 11:28.000
You do Richard.
I'm good to walk.

11:28.000 --> 11:29.750
Sorry about the floor.

11:29.750 --> 11:31.250
I'm gonna call Link.

11:32.670 --> 11:34.080
Oof.
Good luck!

11:36.460 --> 11:37.290
Are we there yet?

11:37.290 --> 11:38.670
To the line you can't cross

11:38.670 --> 11:39.790
unless you're a patient
or doctor?

11:39.790 --> 11:41.880
Uh, no. Why?

11:41.880 --> 11:43.250
Samar: Wait! Doctors!

11:43.250 --> 11:44.830
That's why.

11:44.830 --> 11:46.460
Just keep going.
He already gave consent.

11:46.460 --> 11:48.040
[ Sighs ]
He's your dad, Daya.

11:49.290 --> 11:51.580
Uh, did you have
a last-minute question?

11:51.580 --> 11:53.830
It's happening again.
Dad, breathe.

11:53.830 --> 11:55.960
Remember?
Please breathe.

11:55.960 --> 11:58.880
Daya, I'm sorry.
I love you.

11:58.880 --> 12:00.710
I can't lose you.
And you're perfect.

12:00.710 --> 12:02.330
You're perfect.
You don't need to change.

12:02.330 --> 12:04.710
I do.
I do need to change.

12:04.710 --> 12:07.620
Dad, I need this change.

12:07.620 --> 12:09.250
Mom wanted this for me.

12:09.250 --> 12:11.290
She wanted me
to be able to smile.

12:11.290 --> 12:13.500
She -- She wanted to be able
to make me smile.

12:13.500 --> 12:15.880
She wanted this,
and she's gone,

12:15.880 --> 12:17.540
and you're using her death
as a reason

12:17.540 --> 12:19.920
to not let me have what
she and I both wanted for me.

12:19.920 --> 12:21.330
That is just --
[ Breathing heavily ]

12:21.330 --> 12:23.460
Okay, you have to breathe.

12:23.460 --> 12:25.790
Do you need
one of those bags?

12:25.790 --> 12:27.920
No, he's okay, right?
Nice and easy.

12:27.920 --> 12:28.960
Just breathe, okay?

12:28.960 --> 12:30.500
[ Exhales shakily ]

12:30.500 --> 12:33.040
Look, Mr. Burman,
we know that her condition

12:33.040 --> 12:34.170
is not life-threatening,

12:34.170 --> 12:36.540
but it is
a very serious challenge.

12:36.540 --> 12:39.120
We all depend on nonverbal
communication every day.

12:39.120 --> 12:40.540
You're doing it right now.

12:40.540 --> 12:41.710
You're not talking,

12:41.710 --> 12:42.830
but we all can see
that you are terrified

12:42.830 --> 12:44.330
and you're panicked,

12:44.330 --> 12:45.790
all because you're scared
for your daughter.

12:45.790 --> 12:46.710
But we have good news.

12:46.710 --> 12:48.460
We know what she has,

12:48.460 --> 12:50.040
and we know exactly
how to fix it.

12:52.330 --> 12:54.750
We just need you to let us
do that for her.

12:54.750 --> 12:55.960
Let us do that for you.

12:55.960 --> 12:58.250
I want to smile, Dad.

12:58.250 --> 13:00.790
I want to be able to smile.

13:00.790 --> 13:02.330
Please.

13:02.330 --> 13:04.290
[ Sighs ]

13:04.290 --> 13:05.380
Okay.

13:05.380 --> 13:12.420
♪♪

13:12.420 --> 13:14.120
Promise me you'll
swipe right at least once

13:14.120 --> 13:15.080
while I'm in surgery.

13:15.080 --> 13:16.580
[ Sighs ]
[ Chuckles ]

13:16.580 --> 13:18.380
Alright.
Daya, you ready?

13:18.380 --> 13:19.330
Are you kidding?

13:19.330 --> 13:21.380
Look at this face.
I am pumped.

13:21.380 --> 13:22.960
-[ Chuckles ]
-Alright.

13:22.960 --> 13:24.580
We got her.

13:24.580 --> 13:33.580
♪♪

13:33.580 --> 13:38.790
♪♪

13:38.790 --> 13:40.830
[ Elevator bell dings ]

13:40.830 --> 13:43.790
♪♪

13:43.790 --> 13:49.920
♪♪

13:49.920 --> 13:51.210
[ Sighs ]

13:51.210 --> 13:53.670
I heard about Richard's EMG.
That's big news.

13:53.670 --> 13:55.210
Yep.
Talk of the hospital.

13:55.210 --> 13:57.880
Well, that and your
spontaneous wedding.
Tom.

13:57.880 --> 13:59.460
Did my invitation
for tonight

13:59.460 --> 14:01.250
get lost in the mail,
or...?

14:01.250 --> 14:02.920
Let's not make this harder
than it already is.

14:02.920 --> 14:04.880
Oh, you're referring to
your impending nuptials

14:04.880 --> 14:05.880
as "hard."

14:05.880 --> 14:07.750
That's a good sign.
I love Owen.

14:07.750 --> 14:08.920
And you love me.

14:08.920 --> 14:10.290
Now you're racing off
to the altar

14:10.290 --> 14:12.080
to try to convince yourself
you can live without me.

14:12.080 --> 14:14.420
Spoiler alert.
You can't.

14:14.420 --> 14:16.710
[ Elevator bell dings ]
This wedding
is happening.

14:16.710 --> 14:20.710
♪♪

14:20.710 --> 14:22.330
You know, I've seen a few
shotgun weddings, Teddy,

14:22.330 --> 14:24.920
but usually, it's not
the bride holding the gun.

14:24.920 --> 14:31.000
♪♪

14:36.420 --> 14:38.290
Everything is looking --

14:38.290 --> 14:39.380
-Oh. Oh, hey.
-[ Exhales sharply ]

14:39.380 --> 14:40.380
What'd I miss?

14:40.380 --> 14:41.790
Just the initial
pelvic exam

14:41.790 --> 14:43.830
that shows that's Amelia's
at five centimeters.

14:43.830 --> 14:44.500
Huh?
Already?

14:44.500 --> 14:46.080
Mm-hmm.
"Huh"?

14:46.080 --> 14:47.250
You didn't feel
any contractions?

14:47.250 --> 14:48.670
Nope.

14:48.670 --> 14:50.750
Maybe a little.

14:50.750 --> 14:51.830
They started
at 9:00 this morning.

14:51.830 --> 14:53.460
What?

14:53.460 --> 14:55.750
You put yourself on the board
for five surgeries.

14:55.750 --> 14:57.290
Well, I thought they were
still Braxton Hicks.

14:57.290 --> 14:58.290
No, no, no, no.

14:58.290 --> 15:00.000
You're definitely
in active labor.

15:00.000 --> 15:01.620
Ugh.
I'm gonna go
get the fetal monitor

15:01.620 --> 15:03.380
so we can
check on the baby.

15:03.380 --> 15:04.380
[ Bed motor whirring ]
[ Sighs ]

15:04.380 --> 15:05.540
What, are you skipping town?

15:05.540 --> 15:07.460
'Cause now is not
the right time to tell me.

15:07.460 --> 15:08.620
No, that's our go-bag.

15:08.620 --> 15:10.580
I packed Bluetooth speakers,
a deck of cards,

15:10.580 --> 15:12.210
trashy magazines,
peanuts.

15:12.210 --> 15:13.790
I hate peanuts.
No, those are for me.

15:13.790 --> 15:15.670
Oh.

15:15.670 --> 15:18.420
Oh, I-I-I'll go get you
some French fries

15:18.420 --> 15:19.670
and -- and the biggest
chocolate bar I can find.

15:19.670 --> 15:22.670
No. S-Stay. Please?

15:22.670 --> 15:25.120
I'm not going anywhere.
[ Chuckles ]

15:25.120 --> 15:27.500
Oh! Ooh!

15:27.500 --> 15:29.000
Ah.

15:29.000 --> 15:30.210
Ah.

15:30.210 --> 15:33.170
It's not in your chest,
okay?

15:33.170 --> 15:35.750
You don't feel pain
when you see something violent?

15:35.750 --> 15:37.210
Like, all over?

15:37.210 --> 15:37.960
No.

15:39.330 --> 15:41.880
Hey. I'm here.
Sorry. I was with Richard.

15:41.880 --> 15:43.920
Oh. Um, how's he --
How's he doing?

15:43.920 --> 15:46.120
[ Sighs ] We're making
some progress, I think.

15:46.120 --> 15:47.620
I hope.

15:47.620 --> 15:49.210
Ouch.
Yeah.

15:49.210 --> 15:50.920
See?

15:50.920 --> 15:54.080
Okay, baseball bat splintered,
went into his chest, obviously.

15:54.080 --> 15:55.580
Yeah, it did.

15:55.580 --> 15:57.580
He has blood
in the pericardial sac,

15:57.580 --> 16:00.790
and that looks dangerously close
to the left atrial appendage.

16:00.790 --> 16:03.290
Uh, you need to put him
on bypass to fix it?

16:03.290 --> 16:05.670
Unlikely,
but I will if it tears.
Okay.

16:05.670 --> 16:06.880
He's a baseball player?

16:06.880 --> 16:08.580
Pitcher in the minors.

16:08.580 --> 16:10.250
About to get called up
to the majors.
Yeah.

16:10.250 --> 16:11.500
Not anytime soon.
Yeah.

16:11.500 --> 16:12.670
[ Cellphone chimes,
computer beeps ]

16:12.670 --> 16:14.620
Ohh. Gosh.
[ Inhales sharply ]

16:14.620 --> 16:17.500
Again, Schmitt, this is not
happening to you, okay?

16:17.500 --> 16:19.710
He worked his whole life
for this!

16:19.710 --> 16:23.460
Do you think her dad will
swipe right, like she asked?

16:23.460 --> 16:25.420
Maybe.

16:25.420 --> 16:27.420
Is that my only
hope now?

16:27.420 --> 16:29.210
A stupid algorithm

16:29.210 --> 16:31.380
that claims to know
who to pair me with?

16:31.380 --> 16:32.920
I don't even know
what I'd put in my profile.

16:32.920 --> 16:34.330
I hate everything.

16:34.330 --> 16:36.540
Well, except mac and cheese
from a box.

16:36.540 --> 16:38.750
You know, this looks like
the appropriate size.
Hayes: Mm-hmm.

16:38.750 --> 16:41.040
Now we just need
to tether the muscle

16:41.040 --> 16:44.290
to the oral commissures
right here and here.

16:44.290 --> 16:46.460
We'll be able to eliminate
that constant frown.

16:46.460 --> 16:47.920
What about you,
Jackson?

16:47.920 --> 16:49.500
Do you use
a dating app?

16:49.500 --> 16:51.000
Wait, what's your
profile picture?

16:51.000 --> 16:54.250
A shirtless selfie of you
on your yacht or on your jet?

16:54.250 --> 16:55.420
You have a jet?

16:55.420 --> 16:56.920
No.

16:56.920 --> 16:58.250
I mean, my family --
[ Clears throat ]

16:58.250 --> 17:00.710
The -- Like, the foundation,
I guess, has a jet.

17:00.710 --> 17:02.210
What about you, Hayes?

17:02.210 --> 17:03.500
Definitely not a jet.

17:03.500 --> 17:04.920
No dating profile,
either.

17:04.920 --> 17:08.000
Right, 'cause you have
your own personal matchmaker.

17:08.000 --> 17:10.710
What's that
supposed to mean?

17:10.710 --> 17:12.000
Ready to close.
Vicryl.

17:12.000 --> 17:13.500
[ Clears throat ]

17:13.500 --> 17:18.880
♪♪

17:18.880 --> 17:24.250
♪♪

17:24.250 --> 17:25.170
[ Sighs ]

17:26.380 --> 17:28.080
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Goldberg to L&D.

17:28.080 --> 17:30.120
Dr. Rachel Goldberg to L&D.

17:32.420 --> 17:33.420
Any word?

17:33.420 --> 17:36.170
[ Sighs ]
They're still in the O.R.

17:37.790 --> 17:41.040
You know, Tom, I'm --
I'm a very proud woman,

17:41.040 --> 17:43.040
but I'm not too proud
to admit

17:43.040 --> 17:44.540
the mistakes I've made
in my life.

17:44.540 --> 17:47.380
And this year -- oof --

17:47.380 --> 17:50.290
this year, I've just
screwed up everything.

17:50.290 --> 17:51.710
[ Sighs ] Uh...
[ Clears throat ]

17:51.710 --> 17:53.210
Uh, I don't know.

17:53.210 --> 17:55.670
Remember that one summer
you came to visit me

17:55.670 --> 17:57.920
at my lake house?

17:57.920 --> 17:59.580
You borrowed my car,

17:59.580 --> 18:01.290
and you forgot to put
the parking brake on.
[ Chuckles ]

18:01.290 --> 18:04.080
As we had dinner, I had to
watch my Saab 99 Turbo...
[ Laughs ]

18:04.080 --> 18:07.170
...roll down the hill and sink
to the bottom of Lake Habeeb.

18:07.170 --> 18:08.380
[ Laughing ]
You said it was the --

18:08.380 --> 18:09.620
that was the first time
you'd seen me cry.

18:09.620 --> 18:10.790
[ Laughs ]

18:10.790 --> 18:13.210
Oh, Tommy.
Tommy.

18:13.210 --> 18:18.750
Well, listen, depending on what
we find out from this biopsy...

18:18.750 --> 18:21.250
I might be coming to ask you

18:21.250 --> 18:23.460
to play a bigger role
in the foundation.

18:23.460 --> 18:25.250
Oh.
Eh, Jackson's
my first choice,

18:25.250 --> 18:27.210
but I just don't want to
pressure him

18:27.210 --> 18:29.380
into doing something
that makes him unhappy.

18:29.380 --> 18:31.920
Kit Cat, the foundation
is your life.

18:31.920 --> 18:33.380
Not as long
as Richard needs me.

18:33.380 --> 18:35.080
Mnh-mnh.

18:35.080 --> 18:37.040
I gave up on him once.

18:37.040 --> 18:38.500
I'm never
doing that again.

18:38.500 --> 18:40.460
Oh.

18:40.460 --> 18:44.000
[ Respirator hissing,
monitor beeping ]

18:44.000 --> 18:47.710
I already informed pathology
to put a rush on the report.

18:47.710 --> 18:49.170
You okay?
[ Chuckles ]

18:49.170 --> 18:51.830
I'd say we should bring in
someone who isn't family...

18:51.830 --> 18:53.620
That person
doesn't exist.

18:53.620 --> 18:55.420
Let's go.

18:55.420 --> 18:56.920
Ten blade.

18:56.920 --> 18:58.500
[ Pounding on window ]
Hey, hey! Hey, stop!

18:58.500 --> 18:59.710
Wait! Don't cut! Okay?

18:59.710 --> 19:01.540
Damn it, DeLuca!
Just stop, okay?

19:01.540 --> 19:03.290
I-I'm sorry,
but I found something.

19:03.290 --> 19:05.170
I was going over
Dr. Webber's history again,

19:05.170 --> 19:07.120
and he got a hip replacement
three years ago in Boston.

19:07.120 --> 19:09.960
Richard Webber
is sedated on the table.

19:09.960 --> 19:11.710
You need to step away
from the sterile field

19:11.710 --> 19:12.880
and wait outside!

19:12.880 --> 19:14.420
And you can tell us about it
when we're finished.

19:14.420 --> 19:16.000
No, no, no.
How about now? Huh?
Are you --

19:16.000 --> 19:17.080
[ Tools clatter ]

19:17.080 --> 19:18.540
Gonna listen to me now?

19:20.790 --> 19:21.790
That's it.

19:21.790 --> 19:23.880
You're done.
Get out.

19:23.880 --> 19:25.170
Uh, we need to
re-sterilize.
Bailey.

19:25.170 --> 19:26.620
No, no, no.
B-Bailey, listen to me, okay?

19:26.620 --> 19:28.710
Look, you don't need to do
the biopsy, alright?

19:28.710 --> 19:30.710
His hip replacement
was made out of cobalt.

19:30.710 --> 19:32.250
We did a heavy metals test.

19:32.250 --> 19:33.920
Wh-- It came back negative,
right?

19:33.920 --> 19:35.380
Not for cobalt.

19:35.380 --> 19:38.380
That test is mercury,
arsenic, and lead.

19:38.380 --> 19:39.330
We wouldn't see that.

19:39.330 --> 19:40.750
Right.

19:40.750 --> 19:43.040
And if that hip is
deteriorating, Bailey,

19:43.040 --> 19:45.670
cobalt poisoning would explain
the dementia, the depression,

19:45.670 --> 19:48.330
hallucinations, tremors --
everything, okay?

19:48.330 --> 19:49.580
And every second
that it stays in his body,

19:49.580 --> 19:50.830
he's --
he's getting sicker.

19:50.830 --> 19:52.540
Bailey, please trust me.

19:52.540 --> 19:55.330
♪♪

19:55.330 --> 19:56.880
Change of plans.

19:56.880 --> 19:58.420
We need to draw some blood.

19:58.420 --> 19:59.420
D--

20:01.210 --> 20:03.170
DeLuca, run this down
to the lab.

20:03.170 --> 20:04.540
Tell them the chief says

20:04.540 --> 20:06.710
move this
to the front of the line.

20:06.710 --> 20:08.210
Run!
Okay. Okay.

20:08.210 --> 20:15.580
♪♪

20:21.040 --> 20:23.250
[ Sighs ]
You really think a hip
replacement

20:23.250 --> 20:24.380
could've caused all this?
Mm-hmm.

20:24.380 --> 20:26.120
Meredith:
It's a metal-on-metal joint,

20:26.120 --> 20:28.290
which means
it's entirely possible

20:28.290 --> 20:30.500
that the friction caused the hip
to wear away over time.

20:30.500 --> 20:32.830
DeLuca: I-I confirmed it with
the hospital in Boston today.

20:32.830 --> 20:35.000
They used a chromium cobalt
alloy for his surgery.

20:35.000 --> 20:36.250
Cobalt in his blood stream

20:36.250 --> 20:38.210
would explain
the neurotoxic symptoms.

20:38.210 --> 20:40.580
Okay, so,
cobalt level's...

20:40.580 --> 20:42.420
200?
Catherine: Oh.

20:42.420 --> 20:44.380
The average level in a healthy
adult male is around 8.

20:44.380 --> 20:46.120
That's 25 times
more than it should be.

20:46.120 --> 20:47.500
How permanent
is this damage?

20:47.500 --> 20:49.040
I-It's not.
It shouldn't be.
You don't know that.

20:49.040 --> 20:50.250
First step is we have to

20:50.250 --> 20:52.380
get that cobalt out of him
and replace it.

20:52.380 --> 20:55.120
Well, go, go!
Get that thing out of him now!

20:55.120 --> 20:57.080
Right.
Alright, Taryn, find an empty
O.R. and prep Dr. Webber.

20:57.080 --> 20:58.330
Hey, I want to scrub in.

20:58.330 --> 21:00.290
And I want a house in Hawaii.
Go home.

21:00.290 --> 21:02.330
Chief, any resident
who found what I found

21:02.330 --> 21:03.460
would get the privilege
to scrub in. Please.

21:03.460 --> 21:04.920
Y-You can't
discriminate against me

21:04.920 --> 21:06.120
because you think
I have a problem.

21:06.120 --> 21:07.920
Lord, I'm sick of you.

21:07.920 --> 21:10.580
Dr. Bailey...
[ Sighs ]

21:10.580 --> 21:13.330
...he doesn't have to
touch Richard, but he's right.

21:13.330 --> 21:14.790
It's his diagnosis.

21:14.790 --> 21:15.920
It's a career
defining moment.

21:15.920 --> 21:17.750
He should get to
be there.

21:17.750 --> 21:18.830
Not a finger.

21:18.830 --> 21:20.250
Thank you.
Scout's honor.
[ Grunts ]

21:20.250 --> 21:22.290
Got to go find
Atticus Lincoln.

21:22.290 --> 21:24.710
Well, he's with Amelia,
and they're having a baby.

21:24.710 --> 21:26.790
[ Chuckles ] Right.

21:26.790 --> 21:28.580
Well, not anymore.

21:28.580 --> 21:30.750
Hey, Mer.
Thank you.

21:30.750 --> 21:33.420
Don't make me
regret this.

21:33.420 --> 21:35.750
I won't.
Meredith: Amazing catch.

21:35.750 --> 21:37.170
Sorry, sorry, sorry, sorry,
sorry, sorry, sorry, sorry.

21:37.170 --> 21:38.790
Ah, doesn't hurt a bit.
Ah.

21:38.790 --> 21:40.750
Actually, you sh--
squeeze harder, actually,

21:40.750 --> 21:42.920
because, uh, because
I'm feeling nothing here.

21:42.920 --> 21:45.540
[ Sighs ]
You're progressing
very nicely, Amelia.

21:45.540 --> 21:48.040
Really?
Because it feels epically slow.

21:48.040 --> 21:49.670
D-- Oh. Dr. Lincoln,

21:49.670 --> 21:51.170
uh, we need you
in O.R. 1,

21:51.170 --> 21:54.290
explantation and replacement
of a hip prosthesis.

21:54.290 --> 21:56.380
Kind of in the middle
of something here.

21:56.380 --> 21:57.880
It's for Richard.

21:57.880 --> 21:59.830
He tested positive
for cobalt toxicity.

21:59.830 --> 22:01.120
It's his hip.

22:01.120 --> 22:02.580
Webber's got
a cobalt hip?

22:02.580 --> 22:04.880
Yeah, which is leaching
more cobalt into his blood

22:04.880 --> 22:05.880
the longer we speak.

22:05.880 --> 22:08.420
I -- I would not ask,

22:08.420 --> 22:10.710
but he needs the best we have,
and he needs it now.

22:10.710 --> 22:12.420
Okay. I think
we're almost done here.

22:12.420 --> 22:14.170
No, you're still
only six centimeters.

22:14.170 --> 22:15.880
You have hours.
What?

22:15.880 --> 22:16.920
Still?
Yeah.

22:16.920 --> 22:19.290
Oh. Okay. Go.

22:19.290 --> 22:20.580
You sure?
Yeah. Yeah, it's Richard.

22:20.580 --> 22:21.620
Go. Go.

22:21.620 --> 22:23.380
Mm. Mwah.

22:23.380 --> 22:25.000
Okay, go.
No, w-wait.

22:25.000 --> 22:26.620
Wait, do that again.

22:26.620 --> 22:28.880
Mm.

22:28.880 --> 22:30.120
Mm. Mm.

22:30.120 --> 22:33.120
♪♪

22:33.120 --> 22:35.000
That really does
help with the pain some.

22:35.000 --> 22:36.710
I told you!

22:36.710 --> 22:37.880
Okay, go, go!

22:37.880 --> 22:39.210
I'm pretty madly
in love with you, you know.

22:39.210 --> 22:40.460
Me, too! Go!

22:40.460 --> 22:42.290
[ Chuckles ]

22:42.290 --> 22:44.210
Bailey!
Huh?

22:44.210 --> 22:45.460
Huh?

22:45.460 --> 22:46.620
[ Exhales sharply ]

22:46.620 --> 22:48.750
Oh, uh, no, I'm gonna
help prep Richard.

22:48.750 --> 22:51.710
You stole the father of my baby
while I'm in active labor.

22:51.710 --> 22:53.000
Uh --

22:53.000 --> 22:55.330
Ha-- Uh --

22:55.330 --> 22:56.750
[ Exhales sharply ]

22:56.750 --> 22:57.960
[ Sighs ]

22:57.960 --> 22:59.000
Oh.

23:00.580 --> 23:02.250
Oh!
What?

23:02.250 --> 23:04.620
Aah!
Aah!

23:04.620 --> 23:07.000
Hayes: No tension.
Perfect coaptation.

23:07.000 --> 23:09.710
Jackson: Just need to anchor
the muscle proximally

23:09.710 --> 23:11.250
and we get to
close her up.

23:11.250 --> 23:13.830
I saw a survey
that said 98% of women

23:13.830 --> 23:16.710
have been told
to smile more at work.

23:16.710 --> 23:19.420
Why is there so much pressure
to smile all the time?

23:19.420 --> 23:21.380
It's not like it makes us
better at our jobs.

23:21.380 --> 23:22.830
The only people
that smile all the time

23:22.830 --> 23:25.000
are clowns
and sociopaths.

23:25.000 --> 23:26.880
Dr. Avery,
are you almost done?

23:26.880 --> 23:28.210
Why?
You need my O.R.?

23:28.210 --> 23:30.210
No, but thank you.

23:30.210 --> 23:31.250
Chief Bailey wanted me
to tell you

23:31.250 --> 23:32.830
we're taking Dr. Webber
to the O.R.

23:32.830 --> 23:34.710
because he has a hip
made of cobalt,

23:34.710 --> 23:36.040
which has been
slowly poisoning him.

23:36.040 --> 23:37.330
Wait, what?
I know.

23:37.330 --> 23:38.960
Dr. DeLuca
figured it out.

23:38.960 --> 23:39.830
DeLuca?

23:39.830 --> 23:40.830
Jackson, go.

23:40.830 --> 23:42.710
We can finish and close.

23:42.710 --> 23:44.080
Got it?
Yep.

23:46.420 --> 23:48.460
Score one for DeLuca.
[ Door opens, closes ]

23:48.460 --> 23:49.830
The way he's been acting,
I'm amazed anyone listened

23:49.830 --> 23:51.040
to anything he had to say,

23:51.040 --> 23:52.620
least of all Grey.

23:52.620 --> 23:56.120
You seem very interested
in who Meredith Grey listens to.

23:56.120 --> 23:58.210
Do I?

23:58.210 --> 24:00.380
I hadn't noticed.

24:00.380 --> 24:02.290
Hmm.

24:02.290 --> 24:04.250
[ Cellphone chiming ]

24:04.250 --> 24:05.710
Schmitt, bovie.

24:05.710 --> 24:07.460
What are the odds

24:07.460 --> 24:10.040
that that thing
would just shatter like that?

24:10.040 --> 24:11.830
Well, maple bats
splinter easily.

24:11.830 --> 24:13.580
Why are they allowed?

24:13.580 --> 24:15.330
Well, they're trying to
phase them out, go back to ash.

24:15.330 --> 24:16.540
Oh, good.

24:16.540 --> 24:18.580
[ Cellphone chimes,
suction hissing ]

24:18.580 --> 24:21.000
Schmitt, can you get that,
please?

24:21.000 --> 24:22.580
Oh, but then I wouldn't
be sterile.

24:22.580 --> 24:23.880
I know.

24:25.750 --> 24:27.250
[ Sighs ]

24:31.210 --> 24:32.080
Okay.

24:32.080 --> 24:34.710
Some guy
named Winston says

24:34.710 --> 24:37.210
that he can't stop
thinking about you.
No, no, no, no.
Not that one.

24:37.210 --> 24:38.750
Okay.

24:38.750 --> 24:41.380
Grey texted, too,
and Bailey and Helm.

24:41.380 --> 24:42.670
Well,
what did they say?

24:42.670 --> 24:44.040
Ooh, it's a lot.
I'm reading.

24:44.040 --> 24:47.500
Dr. Webber has cobalt poisoning
from a hip replacement,

24:47.500 --> 24:49.620
and they're rushing him
into surgery to replace it.

24:49.620 --> 24:51.880
They think that it
explains everything
that's wrong with him.

24:51.880 --> 24:54.830
♪♪

24:54.830 --> 24:56.790
Pierce, we can -- we can
page Altman if you need to --

24:56.790 --> 24:59.830
No. No.
I'm -- I'm okay.

24:59.830 --> 25:01.330
I just need a second.

25:01.330 --> 25:04.830
[ Inhales deeply,
exhales sharply ]

25:04.830 --> 25:07.330
Okay. Bovie.

25:07.330 --> 25:12.420
♪♪

25:12.420 --> 25:14.380
[ Knock on door ]

25:14.380 --> 25:16.040
Teddy: [ Sighs ]

25:20.250 --> 25:21.420
You're the one who paged.

25:21.420 --> 25:22.750
Mm.

25:28.170 --> 25:29.120
I'm driving across
the Key Bridge

25:29.120 --> 25:31.790
in Baltimore
one night, early June,

25:31.790 --> 25:34.920
sunset, weather's gorgeous,
slight breeze,

25:34.920 --> 25:36.790
sailboats on the water.

25:36.790 --> 25:38.120
There was a crimson sky.

25:38.120 --> 25:40.170
Tom.
A-And I see this guy,

25:40.170 --> 25:41.580
20-something,
on his phone,

25:41.580 --> 25:42.960
looking distraught,

25:42.960 --> 25:44.830
his face all
tightened up in anguish,

25:44.830 --> 25:47.080
and he's leaning way out
over the railing.

25:47.080 --> 25:49.210
And before I know what
I'm doing, I slam on my brakes,

25:49.210 --> 25:50.880
I run to him --
"Don't do it! Don't --"

25:50.880 --> 25:53.080
Cars lined up behind mine,
people leaning on their horns,

25:53.080 --> 25:54.750
but I had to stop him.

25:54.750 --> 25:57.000
I-I -- At least try.

25:57.000 --> 25:59.380
I couldn't let him
throw his life away.

25:59.380 --> 26:01.620
So, what happened?
Did you talk him down?
Oh, no.

26:01.620 --> 26:04.210
It turns out he was just calling
into a radio station

26:04.210 --> 26:05.380
for some
free concert tickets,

26:05.380 --> 26:07.460
and the reception was better
out over the water.

26:07.460 --> 26:10.500
I just wanted to tell a story
to illustrate my point.

26:10.500 --> 26:12.120
[ Sighs ]

26:12.120 --> 26:14.080
Don't throw your life away,
Teddy.

26:14.080 --> 26:16.040
I hate that I have
dragged you into this.

26:16.040 --> 26:17.540
I hate
that I'm hurting you.

26:17.540 --> 26:18.580
Because you love me.

26:18.580 --> 26:19.790
I am marrying Owen.

26:19.790 --> 26:21.330
And I love you, too.

26:21.330 --> 26:22.580
Which means
I'm not giving up on you.

26:22.580 --> 26:26.210
So, tonight,
I'll be in my car.

26:26.210 --> 26:30.250
Lot B, 7:00.

26:30.250 --> 26:31.250
Waiting...

26:31.250 --> 26:34.000
♪ You and I ♪

26:34.000 --> 26:35.750
...to take you
wherever you want to go.

26:35.750 --> 26:38.620
You want to go out
to your place? Hmm?

26:38.620 --> 26:40.670
Explain things to Hunt?
Fine.
[ Sighs ]

26:40.670 --> 26:43.880
You want to run away,
go down the coast,

26:43.880 --> 26:46.960
spend a weekend...
figuring things out?

26:49.250 --> 26:53.040
I'll be there. 7:00.

26:53.040 --> 26:54.120
Tom.

26:54.120 --> 26:55.460
♪ Be over before we know it ♪

26:55.460 --> 26:56.750
We can't do this.

26:58.420 --> 26:59.710
Say it.

26:59.710 --> 27:01.880
[ Breathes sharply ]

27:03.250 --> 27:04.790
I love you, too.
Mm.

27:04.790 --> 27:06.540
[ Breathing heavily ]

27:06.540 --> 27:08.710
Mm.

27:08.710 --> 27:10.580
♪ Don't even try ♪

27:10.580 --> 27:12.920
♪ Don't look for a reason ♪

27:12.920 --> 27:15.250
♪ This isn't the end ♪

27:15.250 --> 27:20.210
♪ It's only a season ♪

27:20.210 --> 27:24.750
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪

27:24.750 --> 27:27.000
[ Respirator hissing ]

27:27.000 --> 27:32.080
♪ A love like ours
will never die ♪

27:32.960 --> 27:36.330
♪ Ooh, ooh, ooh ♪

27:36.330 --> 27:41.500
♪ A love like ours
